<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10054b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10054b">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10054b"> 54(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> teleautographic xx</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">C&apos;est le seul moyen pratique de conna&icirc;tre la rapidit&eacute; de votre train, puis, c&apos;est une distraction comme une autre, une occasion de remuer quelques chiffres, quand vous &ecirc;tes bien assis dans votre coin; quand vous regardez, par le cadre des fen&ecirc;tres, d&eacute;filer les poteaux <mark>t&eacute;l&eacute;graphiques</mark>, dont les fils montent et descendent sous vos yeux avec une monotonie fatigante; quand vous voyez en face de vous, un monsieur important et grave, qui d&eacute;ploie lentement son journal, et le lit avec la mine rogue d&apos;un pr&eacute;sident d&apos;assises; quand &agrave; votre gauche, un gentleman Anglais qui s&apos;allonge sur la banquette met ses deux pieds dans vos poches et ronfle, apr&egrave;s la premi&egrave;re station, comme la chaudi&egrave;re d&apos;un cuirass&eacute; de <i>Her Gracions Majesty</i>. <font color="green">[This is the only practical means of establishing the speed of your train, and it is a diversion like any other, an occasion to juggle numbers, while you sit nicely in your corner; when you look through the frame of the windows and see the telegraph poles pass by, and the lines go up and down in a tiresome monotony; when you see ahead of you, a serious and important person, who slowly opens his newspaper and reads it with the gravity of a federal judge; when at your right an English gentleman lies down on the bench with his two feet in your pockets and snores, after the first station, like the engines of one of <i>Her Gracious Majesty</i>&apos;s ships]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 153</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Telautographic. Pertaining to the telautograph, a telegraphic device invented by Elisha Gray in the 1880s, enabling telegraphic transmission of writing or drawing. Joyce&apos;s note seems to be referring to the transmission of kisses, signified by writing x at the end of letters. </mm> </dd></dl>
